A Better Year for Migrants?
DUBLIN – Two major lessons emerge from the migration crisis in the Mediterranean.
First, Europe and the international community apply a cruelly ill-suited system for protecting the most vulnerable migrants.
Second, in the face of the ineffectiveness of this system, populist actors continue to exploit fears in order to gain political support, undermining liberal and tolerant societies that took some 70 years of determined effort to build.
This is why it is essential that such an active approach be undertaken this year at both European and global levels.
In September, United Nations Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon will convene an extraordinary summit aimed at building a robust global protection system for the most vulnerable migrants and refugees.
Let us hope that states will be ready to engage concretely and sustainably.
This necessary engagement has sadly been lacking throughout the year 2015.
Indeed, the international community could have limited the severity of last year's crisis if it had provided even the most modest support to the frontline countries – Turkey, Lebanon, and Jordan – which together host no fewer than four million refugees.
With only about 10 billion euros, these countries would have been better able to house, feed, and provide education to the refugees, thereby reducing the temptation to flee to Europe.
This failure could cost Germany alone up to 21 billion euros every year in the years to come.
But the financial implications of the crisis are without comparison to its human and political costs.
More than a million people risked their lives last year crossing the Mediterranean, enduring a draining journey through the Balkans thereafter.
Close to 4,000 migrants lost their lives there, with many European countries turning their backs on the survivors by refusing them sanctuary.
The most cynical political actors have mercilessly exploited citizens' fears, promoting a hateful nationalist narrative that either ignores or distorts the migrant experience.
In the United States, for example, not one of the 780,000 refugees installed since September 11, 2001 has been guilty of terrorist acts.
At the same time, immigrants generally pay more in taxes than they receive in social benefits.
And yet, extremist parties are dangerously flirting with taking political power in some European countries, and are currently gaining support even within long-standing liberal strongholds.
Anti-immigration parties are already in power in Hungary and Poland.
Their success also leads traditional parties to promote an immigration-hostile policy themselves.
This situation has considerably undermined European cooperation.
The EU program aimed at caring for the million of refugees arriving on its shores managed to relocate only 190 of them.
Borders controls have been reinstated in at least provisionally in the territories of six Schengen countries.
To the rest of the world, the EU appears today chauvinistic and incompetent.
Naturally, resolving this crisis is not solely Europe's responsibility; geographical proximity cannot define accountability.
However, the EU undoubtedly faces today a threat to its very existence, which it will overcome only by demonstrating firm solidarity and international leadership of which it is capable.
This is why it is up to the member states to take the initiative by proposing solutions.
The highest priority is to establish legal and secure pathways for refugees to reach Europe.
This is not to say that every migrant in difficulty must be welcomed.
It remains, however, for the EU to be more systematically generous in its determination of the number of refugees to welcome, and to use orderly mechanisms aimed at facilitating their entry.
A system like this would allow for protecting migrants while safeguarding Europe (thanks to the possibility of fully examining the applications).
Beyond an approach aimed at deterring asylum seekers from risking their lives crossing the Mediterranean, such an approach would also project an image of solidarity towards the frontline countries, which continue to house the majority of refugees.
An equally important aspect, this approach would encourage the rest of the international community to contribute to these efforts.
This leads us to the second priority for 2016: building a robust global system for protecting vulnerable refugees and migrants.
This objective will require, above all, that more countries agree to host refugees.
Over the past few years, the United Nations Refugee Agency has managed to resettle only slightly more than 75,000 of the approximately 20 million annual refugees.
Many end up in a state of prolonged migration, with an average duration estimated at 25 years, trapped in a sort of purgatory and uncertain about the day they might return home.
In 2016, developed countries must agree to welcome a cumulative number close to one million refugees annually, either through resettlement or by granting humanitarian, student, professional, or other visas.
With Canada stating it will take in 50,000 Syrian refugees this year, this objective is clearly achievable.
At the same time, the international community must support the integration of refugees in important host countries such as Turkey, Kenya, Lebanon, and Jordan.
In the current state of affairs, these countries receive only a fraction of the $3,000 to $5,000 annually needed for each refugee for housing, food, care, education, and vocational training during the first years of resettlement.
And these figures do not account for the necessary cost of construction or upgrading infrastructure.
In Lebanon, for example, water supply systems suffer under the pressure of the massive influx of refugees.
In exchange for funding, these host countries could commit to fully integrating refugees into their schools, labor market, and civic institutions.
But effective integration of migrants will be possible only if countries in Europe and elsewhere rid themselves of their prejudices against migrants.
Si these remain considered as a burden, even a threat to security, the reactionary political forces will continue to gain ground, depriving newcomers of opportunities and transforming fear into a self-fulfilling prophecy.
On the other hand, if the host states manage to integrate the migrants with enthusiasm, everyone will benefit – including these countries (particularly through financial entries).
Last month, in Paris, the international community proved it was capable of subordinating its national interests to a broader global objective: the fight against climate change.
In 2016, a similar effort is needed to build a better protection system for migrants.
This is a matter of life or death for some 20 million refugees, for several other vulnerable migrants – as well as a profound test of the civic health of democratic societies around the world.
